{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504042","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504042"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:09:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:09:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2291"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2291","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2291"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.06,0.18,0.01,0.64]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2291"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"39097"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2291","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2291"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2291"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"23423"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1009"},{"type":"tags","id":"1108"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"557"},{"type":"contributions","id":"570"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1106"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2919"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3809"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43119"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"39097","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/39097"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 79-year-old nursing home resident with a background of Alzheimer\u2019s disease has become increasingly agitated over the last month. He has been disruptive at meal times and is constantly rude and aggressive to nursing staff. The staff of the nursing home call his primary care provider and request this resident to be transferred to the acute geriatric unit at a metropolitan hospital. Apart from these disruptive behaviours, he has exhibited no changes to his attention and no behavioural disturbances. He sleeps well at night and does not report any significant physical symptoms. He is not on any current medication.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be the most appropriate next step for the primary care provider to take?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Start on a low-dose risperidone","Start on a cholinesterase inhibitor","Discuss mood and behaviour with the patient\u0027s next-of-kin/family","Admit to the acute psychiatric unit","Obtain a further history from the nursing staff about their particular concerns for this patient"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis nursing home resident\u2019s disruptive behaviour occurs primarily during meal times and does not suggest delirium or any progression of worsening dementia. This behaviour can be modifiable or accommodated perhaps by giving him time and space to speak during mealtimes. It is important to \u003Cstrong\u003Ediscuss his recent mood or behaviours with the nursing staff\u003C/strong\u003E whilst on the telephone and then to contact the patient\u0027s family to discern if there were any particular reason for his disruptive behaviour during his mealtimes. Asking his family how he normally partake his meals at home could give clues as to why he is acting out this way during mealtimes. This should be done before involving further management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrescribing drugs for dementia patients without an appropriate cause is bad practice. This may result in significant unnecessary adverse effects from the medication without treating and understanding the underlying cause of such behaviour. Side effects include somnolence, dry mouth, weight gain, insomnia and hyperprolactinaemia. There are also reports that show an increased risk of cerebrovascular adverse events from olanzapine and risperidone in clinical trials of elderly demented patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdmitting this patient to any acute unit would be unnecessary as this patient is not delirious and has no acute medical or psychiatric condition.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Avoid pharmacological interventions in elderly patients with dementia! Always start with non-pharmacological interventions unless there is evidence of harm to self or others."],"references":["Kirkham J, Sherman C, Velkers C, Maxwell C, Gill S, Rochon P et al. Antipsychotic Use in Dementia. The Canadian Journal of Psychiatry. 2016;62(3):170-181.","Mazzucco, S, Cipriani, A, Barbui, C. (2008) Antipsychotic drugs and cerebrovascular events in elderly patients with dementia: A systematic review. Mini Rev Med Chem 8: 776\u2013783.","Sacchetti, E, Turrina, C, Valsecchi, P (2010b) Cerebrovascular accidents in elderly people treated with antipsychotic drugs: A systematic review. Drug Saf 33: 273\u2013288.","Wooltorton, E (2004) Olanzapine (Zyprexa): Increased incidence of cerebrovascular events in dementia trials. CMAJ 170: 1395."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"23423"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2291"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"23423","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/23423"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-08-25T09:18:41+09:30","updatedAt":"2023-08-25T09:18:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2291"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"39097"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"r